{"title_page": "Brady Street Cemetery", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date= May 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cemetery\n| name        = Bardy Street Cemetery\n| image       = Whitechapel, Jewish cemetery (geograph 3132985).jpg\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = The cemetery today\n| map_type    = United Kingdom Greater London\n| map_size    = \n| map_caption = \n| coordinates = \n| established = 1761\n| country     = England\n| location    = Brady Street, [[Whitechapel]], ([[London Borough of Tower Hamlets]]), London E1\n| type        = [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox Jewish]]\n| style       = \n| owner       = [[United Synagogue]] Burial Society\n| size        = {{convert|4|acre|ha}}\n| graves      = \n| interments  = \n| website     = [https://www.theus.org.uk/article/brady-street-cemetery Brady Street Cemetery]\n| findagrave  = [https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/2200921/brady-street-cemetery  Brady Street Cemetery]\n| political   = \n}}\n\nThe '''Brady Street Cemetery''' is a disused Jewish cemetery on [[Brady Street]] in [[Whitechapel]] in the [[East End of London]], [[E postcode area|E1]]. The cemetery opened in 1761 as the burial ground for the New Synagogue and was subsequently used by the [[Great Synagogue of London|Great Synagogue]]. It closed in 1857. Several notable people are buried there.\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Brady Street Cemetery on 1870s Ordnance Survey map.jpg|thumb|upright|The cemetery marked as the ''Jews' Burial Ground (Disused)'' on an 1870s Ordnance Survey map when Brady Street was known as North Street]]\nThe cemetery is {{convert|4|acre|ha}} in size and is surrounded by a wall topped with broken glass.<ref name='USBrady'>{{cite web|title=Brady Street Cemetery|url=https://www.theus.org.uk/article/brady-street-cemetery|publisher=[[United Synagogue]]|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"BardMiles2017\">{{cite book|author1=Robert Bard|author2=Adrian Miles|title=London's Hidden Burial Grounds|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G0AsDgAAQBAJ|date=15 February 2017|publisher=[[Amberley Publishing]]|isbn=978-1-4456-6112-4|page=109}}</ref> The ''London: East'' edition of the [[Pevsner Architectural Guides]] describes the cemetery as \"crowded with mainly later Victorian monuments\" and highlights Miriam Levy's monument for its \"considerable lavishness\".<ref name=\"CherryO'Brien2005\">{{cite book|author1=[[Bridget Cherry]]|author2=[[Charles O'Brien]]|author3=[[Nikolaus Pevsner]]|title=London: East|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EW7k2KA4UkwC|year=2005|publisher=[[Yale University Press]]|isbn=978-0-300-10701-2|page=559}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe land the cemetery occupies was originally a brickfield on '''Ducking Pond Lane''' and was subsequently known as '''North Street'''. In 1761 it was leased to the New Synagogue for an annual rent of 12 [[Guinea (coin)|guineas]].<ref name=\"MellerParsons2011\">{{cite book|author1=Hugh Meller|author2=Brian Parsons|title=London Cemeteries: An Illustrated Guide & Gazetteer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GmaPAwAAQBAJ|date=1 July 2011|publisher=[[History Press]]|isbn=978-0-7524-9690-0}}</ref> The cemetery was extended in 1795.<ref name=\"HibbertWeinreb2008\">{{cite book|author1=[[Christopher Hibbert]]|author2=[[Ben Weinreb]]|title=The London Encyclopaedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wN_H-__MBpYC|year=2008|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]]|isbn=978-1-4050-4924-5|page=139}}</ref>\n\nThe Brady Street Cemetery rapidly filled, and a solution was found with the addition of a four-foot layer of soil in the centre of the cemetery to allow additional burials. The raised area became known as the \"Strangers Mound\" as many of the new burials were not affiliated to any particular congregation.<ref name=\"BardMiles2017\"/> The headstones of the burials in the Strangers Mound and the ones below are set back to back.<ref name=\"MellerParsons2011\"/> The Great Synagogue subsequently buried people in the New Synagogue's [[West Ham Jewish Cemetery|Jewish cemetery at West Ham]] after forming a Conjoint Burial Board with the New Synagogue.<ref name=\"Alderman1998\">{{cite book|author=[[Geoffrey Alderman]]|title=Modern British Jewry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MKWEwUxMSQEC|year=1998|publisher=Clarendon Press|isbn=978-0-19-820759-7|page=86}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s the local council intended to redevelop the cemetery with the use of a [[compulsory purchase order]] as it had not been used for many years. If a cemetery has not had any interments for 100 years it may be redeveloped, but with the burial of [[Victor Rothschild, 3rd Baron Rothschild]] in the cemetery in 1990, the future of the Brady Street Cemetery was secured from building development until at least 2090.<ref name=\"Bard\">{{Cite book |author= Robert Bard |title=Whitechapel & Stepney Through Time |publisher=[[Amberley Publishing]]  |year=2014 |location=[[Stroud, Gloucestershire]]|ISBN= 9781445642123}}</ref><ref name='JewEast'>{{cite web|title=Jewish East End of London \u2013 Brady Street Cemetery|url=https://www.jewisheastend.com/brady.html|author= Philip Walker|website=Jewish East End|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe cemetery is owned by the [[United Synagogue]] and open only by appointment.<ref name='USBrady'/>\n\n==Notable burials==\n\n*Financiers [[Goldsmid family|Benjamin (c. 1753\u20131808) and Abraham (c. 1756\u20131810) Goldsmid]], both of whom committed suicide\n*Rabbi of Great Britain [[Solomon Hirschell]] (1762\u20131842)<ref name='USBrady'/>\n* [[Hyman Hurwitz]] (1770\u20131844), the first professor of Hebrew at [[University College, London]]<ref name='USBrady'/>\n*Charity worker [[Miriam Levy]] (1801\u20131850)<ref name='USBrady'/>\n*Centenarian Nathan Moses who died aged 107 in 1799\n*Banker [[Nathan Meyer Rothschild]] (1777\u20131836) and his wife Hannah Rothschild (n\u00e9e Barent-Cohen, 1783\u20131850)<ref name='USBrady'/>\n*Business executive and intelligence operative [[Victor Rothschild, 3rd Baron Rothschild]] (1910\u20131990)<ref name=\"Bard\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Jewish cemeteries in the London area]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Brady Street Cemetery}}\n*{{Official|https://www.theus.org.uk/article/brady-street-cemetery}}\n*[http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/gardens-online-record.php?ID=THM012  London Gardens Online: Brady Street Cemetery]\n*[http://www.cemeteryscribes.com/showmap.php?cemeteryID=3&tree=Cemeteries Complete photographic record of headstones at the Brady Street Cemetery at CemeteryScribes]\n\n{{coord|51.5219|-0.0608|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:1760s in London]]\n[[Category:1761 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:1858 disestablishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ashkenazi Jewish culture in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Bethnal Green]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Whitechapel]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in London]]\n[[Category:Jewish cemeteries in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{For|the Liberal Jewish Cemetery |Liberal Jewish Cemetery, Willesden}}\n{{EngvarB|date= May 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cemetery\n| name        = Bardy Street Cemetery\n| image       = Whitechapel, Jewish cemetery (geograph 3132985).jpg\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = The cemetery today\n| map_type    = United Kingdom Greater London\n| map_size    = \n| map_caption = \n| coordinates = \n| established = 1761\n| country     = England\n| location    = Brady Street, [[Whitechapel]], ([[London Borough of Tower Hamlets]]), London E1\n| type        = [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox Jewish]]\n| style       = \n| owner       = [[United Synagogue]] Burial Society\n| size        = {{convert|4|acre|ha}}\n| graves      = \n| interments  = \n| website     = [https://www.theus.org.uk/article/brady-street-cemetery Brady Street Cemetery]\n| findagrave  = [https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/2200921/brady-street-cemetery  Brady Street Cemetery]\n| political   = \n}}\n\nThe '''Brady Street Cemetery''' is a disused Jewish cemetery on [[Brady Street]] in [[Whitechapel]] in the [[East End of London]], [[E postcode area|E1]]. The cemetery opened in 1761 as the burial ground for the New Synagogue and was subsequently used by the [[Great Synagogue of London|Great Synagogue]]. It closed in 1857. Several notable people are buried there.\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Brady Street Cemetery on 1870s Ordnance Survey map.jpg|thumb|upright|The cemetery marked as the ''Jews' Burial Ground (Disused)'' on an 1870s Ordnance Survey map when Brady Street was known as North Street]]\nThe cemetery is {{convert|4|acre|ha}} in size and is surrounded by a wall topped with broken glass.<ref name='USBrady'>{{cite web|title=Brady Street Cemetery|url=https://www.theus.org.uk/article/brady-street-cemetery|publisher=[[United Synagogue]]|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"BardMiles2017\">{{cite book|author1=Robert Bard|author2=Adrian Miles|title=London's Hidden Burial Grounds|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G0AsDgAAQBAJ|date=15 February 2017|publisher=[[Amberley Publishing]]|isbn=978-1-4456-6112-4|page=109}}</ref> The ''London: East'' edition of the [[Pevsner Architectural Guides]] describes the cemetery as \"crowded with mainly later Victorian monuments\" and highlights Miriam Levy's monument for its \"considerable lavishness\".<ref name=\"CherryO'Brien2005\">{{cite book|author1=[[Bridget Cherry]]|author2=[[Charles O'Brien]]|author3=[[Nikolaus Pevsner]]|title=London: East|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EW7k2KA4UkwC|year=2005|publisher=[[Yale University Press]]|isbn=978-0-300-10701-2|page=559}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe land the cemetery occupies was originally a brickfield on '''Ducking Pond Lane''' and was subsequently known as '''North Street'''. In 1761 it was leased to the New Synagogue for an annual rent of 12 [[Guinea (coin)|guineas]].<ref name=\"MellerParsons2011\">{{cite book|author1=Hugh Meller|author2=Brian Parsons|title=London Cemeteries: An Illustrated Guide & Gazetteer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GmaPAwAAQBAJ|date=1 July 2011|publisher=[[History Press]]|isbn=978-0-7524-9690-0}}</ref> The cemetery was extended in 1795.<ref name=\"HibbertWeinreb2008\">{{cite book|author1=[[Christopher Hibbert]]|author2=[[Ben Weinreb]]|title=The London Encyclopaedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wN_H-__MBpYC|year=2008|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]]|isbn=978-1-4050-4924-5|page=139}}</ref>\n\nThe Brady Street Cemetery rapidly filled, and a solution was found with the addition of a four-foot layer of soil in the centre of the cemetery to allow additional burials. The raised area became known as the \"Strangers Mound\" as many of the new burials were not affiliated to any particular congregation.<ref name=\"BardMiles2017\"/> The headstones of the burials in the Strangers Mound and the ones below are set back to back.<ref name=\"MellerParsons2011\"/> The Great Synagogue subsequently buried people in the New Synagogue's [[West Ham Jewish Cemetery|Jewish cemetery at West Ham]] after forming a Conjoint Burial Board with the New Synagogue.<ref name=\"Alderman1998\">{{cite book|author=[[Geoffrey Alderman]]|title=Modern British Jewry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MKWEwUxMSQEC|year=1998|publisher=Clarendon Press|isbn=978-0-19-820759-7|page=86}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s the local council intended to redevelop the cemetery with the use of a [[compulsory purchase order]] as it had not been used for many years. If a cemetery has not had any interments for 100 years it may be redeveloped, but with the burial of [[Victor Rothschild, 3rd Baron Rothschild]] in the cemetery in 1990, the future of the Brady Street Cemetery was secured from building development until at least 2090.<ref name=\"Bard\">{{Cite book |author= Robert Bard |title=Whitechapel & Stepney Through Time |publisher=[[Amberley Publishing]]  |year=2014 |location=[[Stroud, Gloucestershire]]|ISBN= 9781445642123}}</ref><ref name='JewEast'>{{cite web|title=Jewish East End of London \u2013 Brady Street Cemetery|url=https://www.jewisheastend.com/brady.html|author= Philip Walker|website=Jewish East End|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe cemetery is owned by the [[United Synagogue]] and open only by appointment.<ref name='USBrady'/>\n\n==Notable burials==\n\n*Financiers [[Goldsmid family|Benjamin (c. 1753\u20131808) and Abraham (c. 1756\u20131810) Goldsmid]], both of whom committed suicide\n*Rabbi of Great Britain [[Solomon Hirschell]] (1762\u20131842)<ref name='USBrady'/>\n* [[Hyman Hurwitz]] (1770\u20131844), the first professor of Hebrew at [[University College, London]]<ref name='USBrady'/>\n*Charity worker [[Miriam Levy]] (1801\u20131850)<ref name='USBrady'/>\n*Centenarian Nathan Moses who died aged 107 in 1799\n*Banker [[Nathan Meyer Rothschild]] (1777\u20131836) and his wife Hannah Rothschild (n\u00e9e Barent-Cohen, 1783\u20131850)<ref name='USBrady'/>\n*Business executive and intelligence operative [[Victor Rothschild, 3rd Baron Rothschild]] (1910\u20131990)<ref name=\"Bard\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Jewish cemeteries in the London area]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Brady Street Cemetery}}\n*{{Official|https://www.theus.org.uk/article/brady-street-cemetery}}\n*[http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/gardens-online-record.php?ID=THM012  London Gardens Online: Brady Street Cemetery]\n*[http://www.cemeteryscribes.com/showmap.php?cemeteryID=3&tree=Cemeteries Complete photographic record of headstones at the Brady Street Cemetery at CemeteryScribes]\n\n{{coord|51.5219|-0.0608|format=dms|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:1760s in London]]\n[[Category:1761 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:1858 disestablishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ashkenazi Jewish culture in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Bethnal Green]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Whitechapel]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in London]]\n[[Category:Jewish cemeteries in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Headhitter", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing style/layout errors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brady_Street_Cemetery"}
