ines|locality in Toowoomba Region|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> In the {{CensusAU|2016}}, The Pines had a population of 48 people.<ref name=Census2016>{{Census 2016 AUS|id=SSC32831|name=The Pines (SSC)|accessdate=20 October 2018|quick=on}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe land use is [[rural residential]] with large acreage blocks.<ref name=\"globe\">{{Queensland Globe|accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nThere are no schools in The Pines. The nearest primary and secondary school to Year 10 is in [[Millmerran]] and the nearest secondary school to Year 12 in is [[Pittsworth, Queensland|Pittsworth]].<ref name=\"globe\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Toowoomba Region}}\n\n[[Category:Toowoomba Region]]\n[[Category:Localities in Queensland]]\n\n\n{{Toowoomba-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type                = suburb\n| name                = The Pines\n| city                = \n| state               = qld\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|-27.9733|150.9677|type:city_region:AU-QLD|display=inline,title}}\n| pop                 = 48\n| pop_year            = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n| pop_footnotes       = <ref name=Census2016/>\n| established         = \n| postcode            = 4357\n| area                = 5.2\n| timezone            = [[AEST]]\n| utc                 = +10:00\n| dist1               = 35.2\n| dir1                = SW\n| location1           = [[Millmerran]]\n| dist2               = 78.5\n| dir2                = WSW\n| location2           = [[Pittsworth]]\n| dist3               = 117\n| dir3                = WSW\n| location3           = [[Toowoomba]]\n| dist4               = 246\n| dir4                = WSW\n| location4           = [[Brisbane]]\n| lga                 = Toowoomba Region\n| stategov            = [[Electoral district of Southern Downs|Southern Downs]]\n| fedgov              = [[Division of Maranoa|Maranoa]]\n| near-n              = [[Condamine Farms, Queensland|Condamine Farms]]\n| near-ne             = [[Condamine Farms, Queensland|Condamine Farms]]\n| near-e              = [[Condamine Farms, Queensland|Condamine Farms]]\n| near-se             = [[Wattle Ridge, Queensland|Wattle Ridge]]\n| near-s              = [[Wattle Ridge, Queensland|Wattle Ridge]]\n| near-sw             = [[Wattle Ridge, Queensland|Wattle Ridge]]\n| near-w              = [[Western Creek, Queensland|Western Creek]]\n| near-nw             = [[Condamine Farms, Queensland|Condamine Farms]]\n}}\n'''The Pines''' is a [[Suburbs and localities (Australia)|locality]] in the [[Toowoomba Region]], [[Queensland]], Australia.<ref name=qpnl>{{cite QPN|48072|The Pines|locality in Toowoomba Region|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref> In the {{CensusAU|2016}}, The Pines had a population of 48 people.<ref name=Census2016>{{Census 2016 AUS|id=SSC32831|name=The Pines (SSC)|accessdate=20 October 2018|quick=on}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe land use is [[rural residential]] with large acreage blocks.<ref name=\"globe\">{{Queensland Globe|accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nThere are no schools in The Pines. The nearest primary and secondary school to Year 10 is in [[Millmerran]] and the nearest secondary school to Year 12 in is [[Pittsworth, Queensland|Pittsworth]].<ref name=\"globe\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Toowoomba Region}}\n\n[[Category:Toowoomba Region]]\n[[Category:Localities in Queensland]]\n\n\n{{Queensland-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SDZeroBot", "label": "safe", "comment": "Stub sorting: replacing Queensland-geo-stub with Toowoomba-geo-stub", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Pines,_Queensland"}
{"title_page": "Alexander Haim Pekelis", "text_new": "{{short description|Ukrainian jurist & scholar}}\n{{Orphan|date=December 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               =  Alexander Haim Pekelis\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              =  <!-- filename only, i.e. without \"File:\" (or \"Image:\") prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         =  Alexander Haim Pekelis\n| birth_date         =  April 1902\n| birth_place        = [[Odessa, Ukraine]]\n| baptised           =  <!-- will not display if birth_date is entered -->\n| disappeared_date   =  <!-- {{disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (disappeared date then birth date) -->\n| disappeared_place  = \n| disappeared_status = \n| death_date         =  December 28, 1946\n| death_place        = [[Shannon, Ireland]]\n| death_cause        = Airplane accident\n| body_discovered    = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates =  <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments          = \n| residence          = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| nationality        = [[Russia]]n\n| other_names        = \n| ethnicity          =  <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| citizenship        = \n| education          = [[University of Florence]], JJD<br/>\n[[Columbia School of Law]], JJD\n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = \n| years_active       = \n| employer           = \n| organization       = \n| agent              = \n| known_for          = [[Jurist]], [[scholarly method|scholar]] and [[activist]]\n| notable_works      = \n| style              = \n| home_town          = \n| salary             = \n| net_worth          =  <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| height             =  <!-- {{height|cm=X}} OR {{height|ft=X|in=Y}}-->\n| weight             =  <!-- {{convert|X|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}} or {{convert|X|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} -->\n| television         = \n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| party              = \n| movement           = \n| opponents          = \n| boards             = \n| religion           =  <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| denomination       =  <!-- Denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| criminal_charge    =  <!-- Criminality parameters should be supported with citations from reliable sources -->\n| criminal_penalty   = \n| criminal_status    = \n| spouse             = \n| partner            =  <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) -->\n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| callsign           = \n| awards             = \n| module             = \n| module2            = \n| module3            = \n| module4            = \n| module5            = \n| module6            = \n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| website            =  \n| footnotes          = \n| box_width          = \n}}\n\n'''Alexander Haim Pekelis''' (April 1902 &ndash; December 28, 1946) was a [[jurist]], [[scholar]] and [[activist]]. He lived and was educated throughout Europe in his early life and was a jurist in pre-fascist Italy before moving to France in 1938 and to the United States in 1941. He became the first foreign-born Editor-in-Chief of the [[Columbia Law Review]]. Despite his short time in the [[United States]] before his untimely death in 1946 at the age of 44, he left his mark on modern United States jurisprudence, his work advocating and foretelling the role social sciences would come to play in deciding legal issues.\n\nPekelis died in a [[plane crash]] in [[Ireland]], at age 44. After his death, his scholarly works and theories were discussed by the [[Karl E. Meyer]], [[Max Ascoli]] and [[Milton R. Konvitz]] among others.\n\n==Early life==\nAlexander Haim Pekelis was born in [[Odessa, Ukraine|Odessa, Russia]] (now Ukraine), which at the time was part of the [[Russian Empire]]. He graduated from Odessa Gymnasium in 1919, before fleeing from [[Russia]] in 1920 at the time of the [[Russian Revolution]]. He moved to [[Leipzig, Germany]] where he studied for a year before moving to [[Vienna, Austria]] until 1924. After living in Vienna for 3 years he immigrated to [[Florence, Italy]] where he studied law. He was educated at the [[University of Florence]], where he graduated with a law degree in 1928.<ref name=Carla>{{cite journal|last1=Pekelis|first1=Carla|title=La mia versione dei fatti|journal=Palermo: Sellerio Editore|date=1996}}</ref>\n\nAn ardent anti-fascist, Pekelis spent a year studying at the [[London School of Economics]] in 1929 through a fellowship award, ironically, from the fascist Ministry of Education of Italy. Two years after his graduation from the University of Florence, his [[graduate thesis]] was published under the Italian title \"ll diritto come volont\u00e0 costante\", (\"The Law as a Constant Will\"). In 1932, he lectured on [[Jurisprudence]] at the University of Florence. Pekelis did not become a professor at the University, however, because the local Fascist party prevented him from doing so, since he had refused to join the party.<ref name=Carla />\n\nHowever,  he became a Professor of [[Jurisprudence]] at the [[Sapienza University of Rome|University of Rome]] in 1935. The Italian Racial Laws, which were first introduced in 1938, prohibited foreign born Jews from practicing law, medicine, and other professions in Italy. Because of this and the general growing antisemitism,  Pekelis and his family left Italy. He moved to [[Paris]] where he practiced law until 1940. When the Germans invaded France, he fled with his young family (his wife, 3 young daughters, and two grandmothers), traveling through [[Vichy France]], Spain and Portugal finally arriving in the United States as a [[refugee]] in 1941.<ref name=Carla />\n\n==Life in the United States==\nIn the  United States he became a professor at the [[New School for Social Research]] as part of what was then called \"The University in Exile.\" While working as a professor, he had to go to law school all over again, also attending [[Columbia School of Law]]. In 1943 he was named the first foreign-born [[Editor-in-Chief]] of the [[Columbia Law Review]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Russian Is Named Editor of Columbia Law Review|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=1 December 1942}}</ref> After his graduation from Columbia, the University created a new post for him and he became the Graduate [[Editor-in-Chief]].\n\nHis scholarly work from 1941 onwards dealt with the need for judicial action to be informed by social and economic realities; what he termed \"A Jurisprudence of Welfare.\"<ref name=milton>{{cite journal|last1=Konvitz|first1=Milton R.|title=Selected Essays of Alexander H. Pekelis|journal=Ithaca: Cornell University Press|date=1950}}</ref> He was one of the first to anticipate that the Supreme Court would become the champion of a liberal social policy that recognized the role of the social sciences in reaching just results.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dr. Max Ascoli Gets Pan American Post|work=The New York Times|date=29 September 1941}}</ref> He wrote, \"Law is too serious a business to be left to lawyers\u2026The greatness of the Supreme Court is manifested in its growing awareness that the issues which confront it, no matter how legal, must of necessity find a composition social, economic or political in nature.\"<ref name=milton /><ref>{{cite news|title=Dr. Alexander H. Pekelis of the commission on law and social action of the American Jewish Congress will address the rally|work=The New York Times|date=24 October 1946}}</ref>\n\nPekelis co-authored an Amicus brief for The American Jewish Congress in the  Ninth Circuit case, Mendez v. Westminster School District. In the brief Pekelis argued that classifications that segregated [[Mexican people|Mexican]] children according to race, are based on \"discriminatory social or legal notions of \u2018inferiority\u2019 or \u2018superiority\u2019\u2019\u2019 and therefore unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Amicus Curiae Brief|journal=[[American Jewish Congress]]|date=1947|page=4}}</ref>\n\nIn 1945 he became Chief Consultant to the Commission on Law and Social Action, [[American Jewish Congress]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Daily News Brief to Challenge FCC|work=The New York Times|date=11 December 1946}}</ref> While in this role, he was the Chairman of the committee that drafted the original [[Laws of New York|New York statute]] against discrimination in education.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bias at Columbia Denied at Hearing - \"Statistics on Jews Offered\"|work=The New York Times|date=14 May 1946}}</ref> The law was later passed after his death.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pekelis Backs Study in the News FCC Case|work=The New York Times|date=2 October 1946}}</ref>\n\nDuring 1946, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published his letters on various topics.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pekelis|first1=Alexander H.|title=Letters to the Times: Control of Broadcasting|work=The New York Times|date=27 November 1946}}</ref> Later that year, on December 28 Alexander Haim Pekelis was killed in a commercial airplane accident in [[Shannon, Ireland]].<ref>{{cite news|title=TWA Liner's Crash in Ireland Kills 12, Injures 11 Others|work=The New York Times|date=26 December 1946}}</ref> He was returning from the World Zionist Congress in Basle where he had served as Labor Delegate.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pole in Plane Dies on Way to Refuge|work=The New York Times|date=29 December 1946}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his death, his work remains a subject of discussion.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grondona|first1=Mauro|title=Alexander Pekelis: The Law, The State and The Individual|publisher=The Italian Academy}}</ref> For example, in 1964 [[Karl E. Meyer]] recognized Pekelis\u2019 vision in an article in The New Statesman. Meyer wrote \n<blockquote>Hardly anybody foresaw the possibility of the judiciary serving as an active instrument of liberal social policy. Perhaps the first to articulate this notion was a European emigre who remains in undeserved obscurity. \"The federal judiciary, led by the Supreme Court,\" Alexander Pekelis wrote in the early 1940s, \"may very well prove to be, in the coming decade, the most liberal of the three branches of the national government.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Meyer|first1=Karl E|title=This Honourable Court|publisher=The New Statesman|date=July 1964}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Further reading==\n* Richard David - ''Justices and Journalists:  The U.S. Supreme Court and the Media'' (p107)\n* Jesse Choper (Catholic University Law) - On the Warren Court and Judicial Review\" (p24. 1)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pekelis, Alex}}\n[[Category:1902 births]]\n[[Category:1946 deaths]]\n[[Category:Columbia Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:The New School faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Odessa]]\n[[Category:University of Florence alumni]]\n[[Category:White Russian emigrants to Germany]]\n[[Category:White Russian emigrants to Italy]]\n[[Category:White Russian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to Germany]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to Italy]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:White Russian emigrants to Ireland]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to Ireland]]\n[[Category:White Russian emigrants to Austria]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to Austria]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ukrainian jurist & scholar}}\n{{Orphan|date=December 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               =  Alexander Haim Pekelis\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              =  <!-- filename only, i.e. without \"File:\" (or \"Image:\") prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         =  Alexander Haim Pekelis\n| birth_date         =  April 1902\n| birth_place        = [[Odessa, Ukraine]]\n| baptised           =  <!-- will not display if birth_date is entered -->\n| disappeared_date   =  <!-- {{disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (disappeared date then birth date) -->\n| disappeared_place  = \n| disappeared_status = \n| death_date         =  December 28, 1946\n| death_place        = [[Shannon, Ireland]]\n| death_cause        = Airplane accident\n| body_discovered    = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates =  <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments          = \n| residence          = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| nationality        = [[Russia]]n\n| other_names        = \n| ethnicity          =  <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| citizenship        = \n| education          = [[University of Florence]], JJD<br/>\n[[Columbia School of Law]], JJD\n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = \n| years_active       = \n| employer           = \n| organization       = \n| agent              = \n| known_for          = [[Jurist]], [[scholarly method|scholar]] and [[activist]]\n| notable_works      = \n| style              = \n| home_town          = \n| salary             = \n| net_worth          =  <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| height             =  <!-- {{height|cm=X}} OR {{height|ft=X|in=Y}}-->\n| weight             =  <!-- {{convert|X|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}} or {{convert|X|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}} -->\n| television         = \n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| party              = \n| movement           = \n| opponents          = \n| boards             = \n| religion           =  <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| denomination       =  <!-- Denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| criminal_charge    =  <!-- Criminality parameters should be supported with citations from reliable sources -->\n| criminal_penalty   = \n| criminal_status    = \n| spouse             = \n| partner            =  <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) -->\n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| callsign           = \n| awards             = \n| module             = \n| module2            = \n| module3            = \n| module4            = \n| module5            = \n| module6            = \n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| website            =  \n| footnotes          = \n| box_width          = \n}}\n\n'''Alexander Haim Pekelis''' (April 1902 &ndash; December 28, 1946) was a [[jurist]], [[scholar]] and [[activist]]. He lived and was educated throughout Europe in his early life and was a jurist in pre-fascist Italy before moving to France in 1938 and to the United States in 1941. He became the first foreign-born Editor-in-Chief of the [[Columbia Law Review]]. Despite his short time in the [[United States]] before his untimely death in 1946 at the age of 44, he left his mark on modern United States jurisprudence, his work advocating and foretelling the role social sciences would come to play in deciding legal issues.\n\nPekelis died in a [[plane crash]] in [[Ireland]], at age 44. After his death, his scholarly works and theories were discussed by the [[Karl E. Meyer]], [[Max Ascoli]] and [[Milton R. Konvitz]] among others.\n\n==Early life==\nAlexander Haim Pekelis was born in [[Odessa, Ukraine|Odessa, Russia]] (now Ukraine), which at the time was part of the [[Russian Empire]]. He graduated from Odessa Gymnasium in 1919, before fleeing from [[Russia]] in 1920 at the time of the [[Russian Revolution]]. He moved to [[Leipzig, Germany]] where he studied for a year before moving to [[Vienna, Austria]] until 1924. After living in Vienna for 3 years he immigrated to [[Florence, Italy]] where he studied law. He was educated at the [[University of Florence]], where he graduated with a law degree in 1928.<ref name=Carla>{{cite journal|last1=Pekelis|first1=Carla|title=La mia versione dei fatti|journal=Palermo: Sellerio Editore|date=1996}}</ref>\n\nAn ardent anti-fascist, Pekelis spent a year studying at the [[London School of Economics]] in 1929 through a fellowship award, ironically, from the fascist Ministry of Education of Italy. Two years after his graduation from the University of Florence, his [[graduate thesis]] was published under the Italian title \"ll diritto come volont\u00e0 costante\", (\"The Law as a Constant Will\"). In 1932, he lectured on [[Jurisprudence]] at the University of Florence. Pekelis did not become a professor at the University, however, because the local Fascist party prevented him from doing so, since he had refused to join the party.<ref name=Carla />\n\nHowever,  he became a Professor of [[Jurisprudence]] at the [[Sapienza University of Rome|University of Rome]] in 1935. The Italian Racial Laws, which were first introduced in 1938, prohibited foreign born Jews from practicing law, medicine, and other professions in Italy. Because of this and the general growing antisemitism,  Pekelis and his family left Italy. He moved to [[Paris]] where he practiced law until 1940. When the Germans invaded France, he fled with his young family (his wife, 3 young daughters, and two grandmothers), traveling through [[Vichy France]], Spain and Portugal finally arriving in the United States as a [[refugee]] in 1941.<ref name=Carla />\n\n==Life in the United States==\nIn the  United States he became a professor at the [[New School for Social Research]] as part of what was then called \"The University in Exile.\" While working as a professor, he had to go to law school all over again, also attending [[Columbia School of Law]]. In 1943 he was named the first foreign-born [[Editor-in-Chief]] of the [[Columbia Law Review]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Russian Is Named Editor of Columbia Law Review|publisher=[[New York Times]]|date=1 December 1942}}</ref> After his graduation from Columbia, the University created a new post for him and he became the Graduate [[Editor-in-Chief]].\n\nHis scholarly work from 1941 onwards dealt with the need for judicial action to be informed by social and economic realities; what he termed \"A Jurisprudence of Welfare.\"<ref name=milton>{{cite journal|last1=Konvitz|first1=Milton R.|title=Selected Essays of Alexander H. Pekelis|journal=Ithaca: Cornell University Press|date=1950}}</ref> He was one of the first to anticipate that the Supreme Court would become the champion of a liberal social policy that recognized the role of the social sciences in reaching just results.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dr. Max Ascoli Gets Pan American Post|publisher=New York Times|date=29 September 1941}}</ref> He wrote, \"Law is too serious a business to be left to lawyers\u2026The greatness of the Supreme Court is manifested in its growing awareness that the issues which confront it, no matter how legal, must of necessity find a composition social, economic or political in nature.\"<ref name=milton /><ref>{{cite news|title=Dr. Alexander H. Pekelis of the commission on law and social action of the American Jewish Congress will address the rally|publisher=New York Times|date=24 October 1946}}</ref>\n\nPekelis co-authored an Amicus brief for The American Jewish Congress in the  Ninth Circuit case, Mendez v. Westminster School District. In the brief Pekelis argued that classifications that segregated [[Mexican people|Mexican]] children according to race, are based on \"discriminatory social or legal notions of \u2018inferiority\u2019 or \u2018superiority\u2019\u2019\u2019 and therefore unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Amicus Curiae Brief|journal=[[American Jewish Congress]]|date=1947|page=4}}</ref>\n\nIn 1945 he became Chief Consultant to the Commission on Law and Social Action, [[American Jewish Congress]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Daily News Brief to Challenge FCC|publisher=New York Times|date=11 December 1946}}</ref> While in this role, he was the Chairman of the committee that drafted the original [[Laws of New York|New York statute]] against discrimination in education.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bias at Columbia Denied at Hearing - \"Statistics on Jews Offered\"|publisher=New York Times|date=14 May 1946}}</ref> The law was later passed after his death.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pekelis Backs Study in the News FCC Case|publisher=[[New York Times]]|date=2 October 1946}}</ref>\n\nDuring 1946, the ''[[New York Times]]'' published his letters on various topics.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pekelis|first1=Alexander H.|title=Letters to the Times: Control of Broadcasting|publisher=[[New York Times]]|date=27 November 1946}}</ref> Later that year, on December 28 Alexander Haim Pekelis was killed in a commercial airplane accident in [[Shannon, Ireland]].<ref>{{cite news|title=TWA Liner's Crash in Ireland Kills 12, Injures 11 Others|publisher=New York Times|date=26 December 1946}}</ref> He was returning from the World Zionist Congress in Basle where he had served as Labor Delegate.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pole in Plane Dies on Way to Refuge|publisher=New York Times|date=29 December 1946}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his death, his work remains a subject of discussion.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grondona|first1=Mauro|title=Alexander Pekelis: The Law, The State and The Individual|publisher=The Italian Academy}}</ref> For example, in 1964 [[Karl E. Meyer]] recognized Pekelis\u2019 vision in an article in The New Statesman. Meyer wrote \n<blockquote>Hardly anybody foresaw the possibility of the judiciary serving as an active instrument of liberal social policy. Perhaps the first to articulate this notion was a European emigre who remains in undeserved obscurity. \"The federal judiciary, led by the Supreme Court,\" Alexander Pekelis wrote in the early 1940s, \"may very well prove to be, in the coming decade, the most liberal of the three branches of the national government.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Meyer|first1=Karl E|title=This Honourable Court|publisher=The New Statesman|date=July 1964}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Further reading==\n* Richard David - ''Justices and Journalists:  The U.S. Supreme Court and the Media'' (p107)\n* Jesse Choper (Catholic University Law) - On the Warren Court and Judicial Review\" (p24. 1)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pekelis, Alex}}\n[[Category:1902 births]]\n[[Category:1946 deaths]]\n[[Category:Columbia Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:The New School faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Odessa]]\n[[Category:University of Florence alumni]]\n[[Category:White Russian emigrants to Germany]]\n[[Category:White Russian emigrants to Italy]]\n[[Category:White Russian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to Germany]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to Italy]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:White Russian emigrants to Ireland]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to Ireland]]\n[[Category:White Russian emigrants to Austria]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to Austria]]\n", "name_user": "Alaney2k", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife in the United States:the work's name is \"The New York Times\"; remove duplicate wlinks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_Haim_Pekelis"}
{"title_page": "Scott Lobdell", "text_new": "{{lead too short|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox comics creator\n| image         = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1960<!--date information sourced from Deutsche Nationalbibliothek data-->}}\n| birth_place      = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| area          = \n| cartoonist    = \n| write         = y\n| pencil        = \n| ink           = \n| letter        = \n| color         =\n| edit          = \n| alias         = \n| signature     = \n| notable works = ''[[X-Men]]''<br />''[[Generation X (comics)|Generation X]]''<br />''[[Red Hood and the Outlaws]]''<br />''[[Teen Titans (comic series)| Teen Titans]]''<br />''[[Superman (comic book)| Superman]]''<br />''[[Alpha Flight]]''<br />''[[Happy Death Day]]''\n| awards        = \n| sortkey       = Lobdell, Scott\n| subcat        = American\n}}\n'''Scott Lobdell''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|l|\u0252|b|d|\u0259l}}; born 1960<!--date information sourced from Deutsche Nationalbibliothek data-->) is an [[People of the United States|American]] [[comic book writer]], known for his work on numerous [[X-Men]] series for Marvel Comics in the 1990s, various work for [[DC Comics]] in the 2010s, namely ''[[Red Hood and the Outlaws]]'' and ''[[Superman (Volume 3)| Superman]]'', and comics for other publishers including the [[The Hardy Boys Graphic Novel|''Hardy Boys: Undercover Brothers'']] series by [[Papercutz (publisher)|Papercutz]]. He wrote the script to the 2017 slasher film ''[[Happy Death Day]]''.\n\n==Career==\n===Early career===\nLobdell did not begin to read comics until he was 17 years old, while lying in bed after lung surgery. Later, he went to college to study [[psychology]], but quit two years later when he began to write. While in college, he wrote for the college newspaper and interviewed Marvel editor [[Al Milgrom]]. Lobdell started submitting various stories to Marvel, but was systematically rejected by various editors, including [[Tom DeFalco]]. Later, DeFalco started editing [[Marvel Comics Presents]] (a bi-weekly book) requiring many writers, pencillers and inkers. Lobdell submitted a story about a character from [[Marvel Super Hero Contest of Champions|Contest of Champions]]. Because the characters involved were rather obscure, DeFalco did not need to extract approval from other editors, and he decided to give Lobdell a chance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XVGQ5km9BuY&feature=list_related&playnext=1&list=SP3E42FDB3CA564492|title=Ask Scott Lobdell, DC Universe Comic Book Writer, Anything!|accessdate=13 January 2019|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\n===Marvel Comics===\nIn the 1990s, Lobdell became known for his work on [[Marvel Comics]]' [[X-Men]]-related titles, specifically ''[[Uncanny X-Men]]'', the main title itself, and the spin-off series that he conceived with artist [[Chris Bachalo]], ''[[Generation X (comics)|Generation X]]''. He wrote the first 28 issues of ''Generation X'', and at one point was writing both main X-Men titles for a lengthy run. ''Generation X'' focused on a number of young mutant students who attempted to become [[superhero]]es in their own right at a separate school with the guidance of veteran X-related characters [[Banshee (comics)|Banshee]] and [[Emma Frost]]. He also had runs with the ''[[Excalibur (comics)|Excalibur]]'' and ''[[X-Factor (comics)|X-Factor]]'' titles. Scott Lobell was the primary creative force behind most of the major X-title related storylines, especially the major cross-overs, throughout a majority of the 1990s, including \"[[X-Cutioner's Song]]\", \"[[Fatal Attractions (comics)|Fatal Attractions]]\", \"[[Phalanx Covenant]]\", \"[[Age of Apocalypse]]\", the \"[[Onslaught (comics)|Onslaught]]\" saga, and \"[[Operation: Zero Tolerance]]\". He returned briefly to Marvel in 2001, to try and tie up loose ends he left behind and wrote one last storyline, dubbed \"Eve of Destruction\".\n\nMany of the concepts and even characters created by Scott Lobdell and fellow X-Men writer [[Fabian Nicieza]] were used throughout the run of the popular 1990s ''[[X-Men: The Animated Series]]''. Lobdell is even referenced in episode #46 of the show, \"One Man's Worth\", where he poses as a human used to fuel [[Trevor Fitzroy]]'s mutant power to travel through time. The scene shows [[Master Mold]] saying \"Lobdell, I have a job for you.\" He is then grabbed by Fitzroy, who absorbs his life energy and creates a time portal.\n\nLobdell had writing stints on Marvel's ''[[Daredevil (Marvel Comics series)|Daredevil]]'','' [[Alpha Flight (comic book)|Alpha Flight]]'' and ''[[The Adventures of Cyclops and Phoenix]]'' [[mini-series]] with artist [[Gene Ha]]. He also wrote several of the first issues of the \"[[Heroes Reborn (comics)|Heroes Reborn]]\" reboots of both [[Iron Man]] and [[Fantastic Four]].\n\nLobdell wrote the 1992 issue of ''Alpha Flight'' in which the superhero [[Northstar (Marvel Comics)|Northstar]] \u2013 originally intended to be gay, but [[closeted]] by the publisher's existing policy against openly LGBT characters \u2013 declared that he is gay,<ref>[http://www.byrnerobotics.com/FAQ/listing.asp?ID=2&T1=Questions+about+Comic+Book+Projects#106] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126025406/http://www.byrnerobotics.com/FAQ/listing.asp?ID=2&T1=Questions+about+Comic+Book+Projects |date=2013-01-26 }}</ref><ref>Mangels, Andy (2006), In and Out: A Brief History of Marvel's 2006 Gay Policies, Prism Comics, retrieved 2009-03-29</ref> in a storyline intended to also address the HIV/AIDS epidemic.<ref>Alpha Flight #106</ref> Royalties from that issue were donated to the Elizabeth Glaser Pediatric AIDS Foundation.\n\n===Other work===\nLobdell wrote the script to ''[[Stan Lee's Mosaic]]'' and an upcoming film from [[POW! Entertainment]] featuring [[Ringo Starr]]. He also participated in the [[Marvel Comics]] and [[Image Comics]] (from [[Jim Lee]]'s [[WildStorm]]) crossover mini-series ''[[WildC.A.T.s/X-Men]]''.\n\nAs of August 2008, Lobdell is the regular writer for ''[[Galaxy Quest (comics)|Galaxy Quest]]'', a series published by [[IDW Publishing]], with art by [[Ilias Kyriazis]], centered on the eve of the relaunch of the ''Galaxy Quest'' series, now titled ''Galaxy Quest: The Journey Continues''.\n\nTo date, he has written the majority of [[The Hardy Boys Graphic Novel]] series by [[Papercutz (publisher)|Papercutz]].\n\nLobdell has also performed as a [[Comedian|stand up comedian]].<ref>\"Bullpen Bulletins,\" Marvel comics cover-dated April 1990.</ref>\n\nLobdell created ''Paranormal Activity: The Search for Katie'' with art from [[Mark Badger]] it was released in December 2009 on [[iPhone]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/34892/exclusive-director-alex-craig-mann-talks-detention-of-the-dead-and-more/|title=Exclusive: Director Alex Craig Mann Talks Detention of the Dead and More|first=|last=thehorrorchick|date=25 June 2012|website=Dread Central|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nLobdell wrote the screenplay for [[Blumhouse Productions|Blumhouse]]\u2019s [[slasher film]] ''[[Happy Death Day]]''. The film was released on October 13, 2017 by [[Universal Pictures]].\n\n===DC Comics===\nIn 2011, Lobdell took on the writing duties for ''[[Red Hood and the Outlaws]]'', which debuted as part of [[DC Comics]]' company-wide title relaunch, [[The New 52]].<ref>[http://www.comicsalliance.com/2011/06/06/nightwing-1-dick-grayson-batman Dick Grayson Returns as Nightwing, New 'Batwing' and 'Red Hood and the Outlaws' Series &#91;Updated&#93; \u2013 ComicsAlliance | Comic book culture, news, humor, commentary, and reviews] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609181013/http://www.comicsalliance.com/2011/06/06/nightwing-1-dick-grayson-batman |date=2011-06-09 }}</ref> and a new ''[[Teen Titans]]'' comic starring Red Robin, [[Superboy]], Wonder Girl, Kid Flash, and three new characters,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bleedingcool.com/2011/06/08/dc-relaunch-scott-lobdell-confirms-hes-writing-superboy-1 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-06-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612004840/http://www.bleedingcool.com/2011/06/08/dc-relaunch-scott-lobdell-confirms-hes-writing-superboy-1/ |archive-date=2011-06-12 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> including the gay Hispanic superhero [[Bunker (comics)|Bunker]].<ref name=\"comicbookresources.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/lobdell-builds-up-gay-teen-with-titans-bunker/|title=Lobdell Builds Up Gay Teen With \"Titans\" Bunker - CBR|website=Cbr.com|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref> His run on Teen Titans ended with Volume 4 Issue 30, the series was relaunched soon afterwards.\n\nIn 2011, Lobdell announced a creator-owned book called ''Awesome'' that he was working on in conjunction with Ilias Kyriazis.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bleedingcool.com/2011/07/19/scott-lobdells-awesome-at-san-diego-comic-con/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-07-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722090904/http://www.bleedingcool.com/2011/07/19/scott-lobdells-awesome-at-san-diego-comic-con |archive-date=2011-07-22 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Lobdell began writing a new ''[[The Flash (comic book)| Flash]]'' book focusing on [[Wally West]] following the limited series ''[[Heroes in Crisis]]'', titled ''Flash Forward'', which began publication in November.\n\n===Awards===\nHis work has won him recognition in the comic books industry, such as a nomination for the ''[[Comics Buyer's Guide]]'' Award for \"Favorite Writer\" in 1997.<ref>[http://users.rcn.com/aardy/comics/awards/ Comic Book Awards Almanac] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051210040849/http://users.rcn.com/aardy/comics/awards/ |date=December 10, 2005 }}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn 2011, his portrayal of [[Starfire (Teen Titans)|Starfire/Koriand'r]] in the first issue of ''Red Hood And The Outlaws'', which \"[[Reboot (fiction)|rebooted]]\" its characters, was criticized by some observers. Mathew Peterson of ''MajorSpoilers.com'' described its version of the character as a \"'perfect-10 love doll imaginary girlfriend'\", and stated that a \"juvenile treatment of sexual matters here renders one of the main characters into nothing more than a punch line, and in a book with only three characters, that\u2019s unforgivable.\"<ref name=\"MS1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.majorspoilers.com/new-52-review-red-hood-the-outlaws-1|title=\"New 52\" Review|last=Peterson|first=Matthew|website=MajorSpoilers.com|accessdate=24 October 2011}}</ref> Andrew Hunsaker of ''Craveonline.com'' said that Lobdell's take \"has reduced Princess Koriand'r of Tamaran into essentially a highly advanced [[RealDoll|Real Doll]]. Complete with installing a lack of memory of anything related to humanity,\"<ref name=\"CrO\">{{cite web|url=http://www.craveonline.com/comics/reviews/174866-new-52-review-red-hood-and-the-outlaws-1|title=New 52 Review: Red Hood and the Outlaws #1|last=Hunsacker|first=Andrew|website=Craveonline.com|accessdate=24 October 2011}}</ref> and that it \"seems as if Lobdell has taken great pains to strip all the emotional motivation behind Kori's gregarious outlook and reduce her to nothing more than a sex vessel. It is pretty insulting not only to women, but to male intelligence to boot.\"<ref name=\"CrO\" /> Laura Hudson, editor-in-chief of [[ComicsAlliance]], wrote that \"There's a difference between writing a female character as sexually liberated, and writing her as wish-fulfillment sex object, but Starfire sure is making a case for the latter in [a] charmless scene\"<ref name=\"CA2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comicsalliance.com/2011/09/21/dc-firestar-sex/|title=Parting Shot: DC's New Starfire, WTF|last=Hudson|first=Laura|website=ComicsAlliance.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015130607/http://www.comicsalliance.com/2011/09/21/dc-firestar-sex|archivedate=15 October 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=24 October 2011|df=}}</ref> wherein Starfire defends her offer to have sex with one of the characters by saying that \"love has nothing to do with it\".<ref name=\"RHO1\">{{cite comic|writer=Lobdell, Scott|penciller=Rocafort, Kenneth|inker=Blond|colorist=Blond|letterer=Mangual, Carlos|editor=Bobbie Chase, Katie Kubert|story=I Fought the Law and Kicked Its Butt!|title=Red Hood and the Outlaws|volume=1|issue=1|date=November, 2011|publisher=DC Comics|location=New York}}</ref> Hudson also cited this characterization of Starfire in a later article, remarking that portrayals of women as sexual objects \"don't support sexually liberated women; they undermine them\".<ref name=\"CA1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comicsalliance.com/2011/09/22/starfire-catwoman-sex-superheroine/|title=The Big Sexy Problem with Superheroines and Their 'Liberated Sexuality'|last=Hudson|first=Laura|website=ComicsAlliance.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025001254/http://www.comicsalliance.com/2011/09/22/starfire-catwoman-sex-superheroine|archivedate=25 October 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=24 October 2011|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Lobdell explained that among the reasons he no longer had a social media presence was the unintended spillover from his personal to professional life, and a run-in he'd had with writer [[Ron Marz]] on [[Twitter]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsarama.com/8155-ron-marz-scott-lobdell-on-racism-politics-social-media.html|title=RON MARZ, SCOTT LOBDELL On Racism, Politics & Social Media|website=Newsarama|language=en|access-date=2019-01-30}}</ref> Lobdell had accused Marz of having a \"brain tumor\" in response to comments in which Marz characterized as \"racist\" complaints by some fans that [[Afro-Latin Americans|Afro-Latino]] character [[Miles Morales]] would replace [[Peter Parker]] in ''[[Ultimate Spider-Man]]'', and that African-American actor [[Laurence Fishburne]] had been cast as [[Perry White]] in the film ''[[Man of Steel (film)|Man of Steel]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsarama.com/8155-ron-marz-scott-lobdell-on-racism-politics-social-media.html|title=RON MARZ, SCOTT LOBDELL On Racism, Politics & Social Media|website=Newsarama|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TdxBNEnSjtw|title=Scott Lobdell - How My Twitter Conversation With Ron Marz Changed My Social Media|publisher=[[YouTube]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617223815/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TdxBNEnSjtw|archive-date=17 June 2014|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Scott Lobdell admitted to sexually harassing comic book artist/writer [[MariNaomi]] on stage during a [[Prism Comics]] panel at Long Beach Comic Con. MariNaomi had submitted an article to XoJane<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xojane.com/it-happened-to-me/marinaomi-harassed-comics-panel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108082218/http://www.xojane.com/it-happened-to-me/marinaomi-harassed-comics-panel|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 January 2014|title=IT HAPPENED TO ME: I Was Sexually Harassed Onstage At a Comic Convention Panel - xoJane|date=8 January 2014|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref> describing how she'd felt harassed by an unnamed fellow panelist, who had questioned her sexuality on stage, made offensive comments about her appearance and Asian features, and made sexually inappropriate jokes about her during the panel. Lobdell later identified himself as the panelist in question, and issued an apology to MariNaomi through [[Heidi MacDonald]] of ComicsBeat.com.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comicsbeat.com/scott-lobdell-i-apologize-to-marinaomi/|title=Scott Lobdell: I apologize to MariNaomi|first=Heidi|last=MacDonald|date=19 December 2013|website=Comicsbeat.com|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Comics===\n* ''[[Angel: After the Fall|Angel: Only Human]]''\n* ''[[The Adventures of Cyclops and Phoenix]]'' (4-issue [[Limited series (comics)|mini-series]])\n* ''[[Alpha Flight]]'' vol. 3 #1\u201312\n* ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer comics|Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'' (with [[Fabian Nicieza]]) #47\u201359\n* ''[[Daredevil (Marvel Comics series)|Daredevil]]'' #376\u2013379\n* ''[[The Darkness (comics)|The Darkness]]'' #23\u201338\n* ''[[Excalibur (comics)|Excalibur]]'' #31, #35\u201341, #53, #58\u201360, #68\u201371, #75\u201382\n* ''[[Fantastic Four]]'' #1\u20133, 4\u20135  (with [[Chris Claremont]], 1998)\n* ''[[Flash (Wally West)| Flash Forward]]'' #1-6\n* ''[[Galaxy Quest (comics)|Galaxy Quest]]'' #1\u20135\n* ''[[Gen\u00b9\u00b3]]'' #45\u201354\n* ''[[Generation X (comics)|Generation X]]'' #1\u201328\n* ''[[Ghostbusters (franchise)#Comics/Manga|Ghostbusters: Displaced Aggression]]'' #1\u20134\n* ''[[Iron Man]]'' #1\u20137 (1996)\n* ''Manifest Eternity'' #1\u20136 (Wildstorm, 2006)\n* ''[[Red Hood and the Outlaws]]'' (vol. 1) #1\u201338, (vol. 2) #1-(ongoing) (retitled ''Red Hood: Outlaw'')\n* ''[[Red Hood/Arsenal]]'' (ongoing)\n* ''[[Uncanny X-Men]]'' #286\u2013349, 350 (with [[Steven Seagle]]), #390\u2013393\n* ''[[Wildcats (comics)|Wildcats]]'' #1\u20139 (1997)\n* ''[[X-Factor (comics)|X-Factor]]'' #90\u201395, #106\n* ''[[X-Men]]'' (vol. 2) #6\u201311, #46\u201369, #110\u2013113\n===Television and film===\n* ''[[Godzilla: The Series]]'' S2 ep.3 (1999)\n* ''[[Man of the House (2005 film)|Man of the House]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Mosaic (film)|Mosaic]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Happy Death Day]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Critters Attack!]]'' (2019)\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{gcdb|type=credit|search=Scott+Lobdell|title=Scott Lobdell}}\n*{{comicbookdb|type=creator|id=1806|title=Scott Lobdell}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1245146}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[Excalibur (comics)|Excalibur]]'' writer| before=[[Chris Claremont]]|\nafter=[[Alan Davis]]| years=1991}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[Uncanny X-Men]]'' writer| before=[[John Byrne (comics)|John Byrne]]| after=[[Steven T. Seagle|Steve Seagle]]| years=1992\u20131997}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[Excalibur (comics)|Excalibur]]'' writer| before=[[Alan Davis]]|\nafter=[[Richard Ashford]]| years=1993}}\n{{succession box | title=[[X-Factor (comics)|''X-Factor'' (vol. 1)]] writer| before=[[Peter David]]|\nafter=[[J. M. DeMatteis|J.M. DeMatteis]]| years=1993}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[Generation X (comics)|Generation X]]'' writer| before=None| after=[[James Dale Robinson|James Robinson]]| years=1994\u20131997}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[Iron Man]]'' writer| before=[[Terry Kavanagh]] | after=[[Jeph Loeb]] | years=1996\u20131997<br/>(with [[Jim Lee]])}}\n{{succession box | title=[[X-Men: Legacy|''X-Men'' (vol. 2)]] writer| before=[[Fabian Nicieza]]| after=[[Mark Waid]]| years=1995\u20131996}}\n{{succession box | title=[[X-Men: Legacy|''X-Men'' (vol. 2)]] writer| before=[[Mark Waid]]| after=[[Joe Kelly (comics)|Joe Kelly]]| years=1996\u20131997}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[Daredevil (Marvel Comics series)|Daredevil]]'' writer| before=[[Joe Kelly (comics)|Joe Kelly]] |after=[[D. G. Chichester|D.G. Chichester]] | years=1998}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[Fantastic Four]]'' writer| before=[[Brandon Choi]] & [[Jim Lee]]| after=[[Chris Claremont]]| years=1998}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[Uncanny X-Men]]'' writer| before=[[Chris Claremont]]| after=[[Joe Casey]]| years=2001}}\n{{succession box | title=[[X-Men: Legacy|''X-Men'' (vol. 2)]] writer| before=[[Chris Claremont]]|\nafter=[[Grant Morrison]]| years=2001}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[Teen Titans]]'' writer| before=[[J.T. Krul]]| after=[[Will Pfeifer]]| years=2011\u20132014}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lobdell, Scott}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American comics writers]]\n[[Category:Obscenity controversies in literature]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics people]]\n[[Category:American screenwriters]]\n", "text_old": "{{lead too short|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox comics creator\n| image         = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1960<!--date information sourced from Deutsche Nationalbibliothek data-->}}\n| birth_place      = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| area          = \n| cartoonist    = \n| write         = y\n| pencil        = \n| ink           = \n| letter        = \n| color         =\n| edit          = \n| alias         = \n| signature     = \n| notable works = ''[[X-Men]]''<br />''[[Generation X (comics)|Generation X]]''<br />''[[Red Hood and the Outlaws]]''<br />''[[Teen Titans (comic series)| Teen Titans]]''<br />''[[Superman (comic book)| Superman]]''<br />''[[Alpha Flight]]''<br />''[[Happy Death Day]]''\n| awards        = \n| sortkey       = Lobdell, Scott\n| subcat        = American\n}}\n'''Scott Lobdell''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|l|\u0252|b|d|\u0259l}}; born 1960<!--date information sourced from Deutsche Nationalbibliothek data-->) is an [[People of the United States|American]] [[comic book writer]], known for his work on numerous [[X-Men]] series for Marvel Comics in the 1990s, various work for [[DC Comics]] in the 2010s, namely ''[[Red Hood and the Outlaws]]'' and ''[[Superman (Volume 3)| Superman]]'', and comics for other publishers including the [[The Hardy Boys Graphic Novel|''Hardy Boys: Undercover Brothers'']] series by [[Papercutz (publisher)|Papercutz]]. He wrote the script to the 2017 slasher film ''[[Happy Death Day]]''.\n\n==Career==\n===Early career===\nLobdell did not begin to read comics until he was 17 years old, while lying in bed after lung surgery. Later, he went to college to study [[psychology]], but quit two years later when he began to write. While in college, he wrote for the college newspaper and interviewed Marvel editor [[Al Milgrom]]. Lobdell started submitting various stories to Marvel, but was systematically rejected by various editors, including [[Tom DeFalco]]. Later, DeFalco started editing [[Marvel Comics Presents]] (a bi-weekly book) requiring many writers, pencillers and inkers. Lobdell submitted a story about a character from [[Marvel Super Hero Contest of Champions|Contest of Champions]]. Because the characters involved were rather obscure, DeFalco did not need to extract approval from other editors, and he decided to give Lobdell a chance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XVGQ5km9BuY&feature=list_related&playnext=1&list=SP3E42FDB3CA564492|title=Ask Scott Lobdell, DC Universe Comic Book Writer, Anything!|accessdate=13 January 2019|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\n===Marvel Comics===\nIn the 1990s, Lobdell became known for his work on [[Marvel Comics]]' [[X-Men]]-related titles, specifically ''[[Uncanny X-Men]]'', the main title itself, and the spin-off series that he conceived with artist [[Chris Bachalo]], ''[[Generation X (comics)|Generation X]]''. He wrote the first 28 issues of ''Generation X'', and at one point was writing both main X-Men titles for a lengthy run. ''Generation X'' focused on a number of young mutant students who attempted to become [[superhero]]es in their own right at a separate school with the guidance of veteran X-related characters [[Banshee (comics)|Banshee]] and [[Emma Frost]]. He also had runs with the ''[[Excalibur (comics)|Excalibur]]'' and ''[[X-Factor (comics)|X-Factor]]'' titles. Scott Lobell was the primary creative force behind most of the major X-title related storylines, especially the major cross-overs, throughout a majority of the 1990s, including \"[[X-Cutioner's Song]]\", \"[[Fatal Attractions (comics)|Fatal Attractions]]\", \"[[Phalanx Covenant]]\", \"[[Age of Apocalypse]]\", the \"[[Onslaught (comics)|Onslaught]]\" saga, and \"[[Operation: Zero Tolerance]]\". He returned briefly to Marvel in 2001, to try and tie up loose ends he left behind and wrote one last storyline, dubbed \"Eve of Destruction\".\n\nMany of the concepts and even characters created by Scott Lobdell and fellow X-Men writer [[Fabian Nicieza]] were used throughout the run of the popular 1990s ''[[X-Men: The Animated Series]]''. Lobdell is even referenced in episode #46 of the show, \"One Man's Worth\", where he poses as a human used to fuel [[Trevor Fitzroy]]'s mutant power to travel through time. The scene shows [[Master Mold]] saying \"Lobdell, I have a job for you.\" He is then grabbed by Fitzroy, who absorbs his life energy and creates a time portal.\n\nLobdell had writing stints on Marvel's ''[[Daredevil (Marvel Comics series)|Daredevil]]'','' [[Alpha Flight (comic book)|Alpha Flight]]'' and ''[[The Adventures of Cyclops and Phoenix]]'' [[mini-series]] with artist [[Gene Ha]]. He also wrote several of the first issues of the \"[[Heroes Reborn (comics)|Heroes Reborn]]\" reboots of both [[Iron Man]] and [[Fantastic Four]].\n\nLobdell wrote the 1992 issue of ''Alpha Flight'' in which the superhero [[Northstar (Marvel Comics)|Northstar]] \u2013 originally intended to be gay, but [[closeted]] by the publisher's existing policy against openly LGBT characters \u2013 declared that he is gay,<ref>[http://www.byrnerobotics.com/FAQ/listing.asp?ID=2&T1=Questions+about+Comic+Book+Projects#106] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126025406/http://www.byrnerobotics.com/FAQ/listing.asp?ID=2&T1=Questions+about+Comic+Book+Projects |date=2013-01-26 }}</ref><ref>Mangels, Andy (2006), In and Out: A Brief History of Marvel's 2006 Gay Policies, Prism Comics, retrieved 2009-03-29</ref> in a storyline intended to also address the HIV/AIDS epidemic.<ref>Alpha Flight #106</ref> Royalties from that issue were donated to the Elizabeth Glaser Pediatric AIDS Foundation.\n\n===Other work===\nLobdell wrote the script to ''[[Stan Lee's Mosaic]]'' and an upcoming film from [[POW! Entertainment]] featuring [[Ringo Starr]]. He also participated in the [[Marvel Comics]] and [[Image Comics]] (from [[Jim Lee]]'s [[WildStorm]]) crossover mini-series ''[[WildC.A.T.s/X-Men]]''.\n\nAs of August 2008, Lobdell is the regular writer for ''[[Galaxy Quest (comics)|Galaxy Quest]]'', a series published by [[IDW Publishing]], with art by [[Ilias Kyriazis]], centered on the eve of the relaunch of the ''Galaxy Quest'' series, now titled ''Galaxy Quest: The Journey Continues''.\n\nTo date, he has written the majority of [[The Hardy Boys Graphic Novel]] series by [[Papercutz (publisher)|Papercutz]].\n\nLobdell has also performed as a [[Comedian|stand up comedian]].<ref>\"Bullpen Bulletins,\" Marvel comics cover-dated April 1990.</ref>\n\nLobdell created ''Paranormal Activity: The Search for Katie'' with art from [[Mark Badger]] it was released in December 2009 on [[iPhone]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/34892/exclusive-director-alex-craig-mann-talks-detention-of-the-dead-and-more/|title=Exclusive: Director Alex Craig Mann Talks Detention of the Dead and More|first=|last=thehorrorchick|date=25 June 2012|website=Dread Central|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nLobdell wrote the screenplay for [[Blumhouse Productions|Blumhouse]]\u2019s [[slasher film]] ''[[Happy Death Day]]''. The film was released on October 13, 2017 by [[Universal Pictures]].\n\n===DC Comics===\nIn 2011, Lobdell took on the writing duties for ''[[Red Hood and the Outlaws]]'', which debuted as part of [[DC Comics]]' company-wide title relaunch, [[The New 52]].<ref>[http://www.comicsalliance.com/2011/06/06/nightwing-1-dick-grayson-batman Dick Grayson Returns as Nightwing, New 'Batwing' and 'Red Hood and the Outlaws' Series &#91;Updated&#93; \u2013 ComicsAlliance | Comic book culture, news, humor, commentary, and reviews] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609181013/http://www.comicsalliance.com/2011/06/06/nightwing-1-dick-grayson-batman |date=2011-06-09 }}</ref> and a new ''[[Teen Titans]]'' comic starring Red Robin, [[Superboy]], Wonder Girl, Kid Flash, and three new characters,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bleedingcool.com/2011/06/08/dc-relaunch-scott-lobdell-confirms-hes-writing-superboy-1 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-06-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612004840/http://www.bleedingcool.com/2011/06/08/dc-relaunch-scott-lobdell-confirms-hes-writing-superboy-1/ |archive-date=2011-06-12 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> including the gay Hispanic superhero [[Bunker (comics)|Bunker]].<ref name=\"comicbookresources.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/lobdell-builds-up-gay-teen-with-titans-bunker/|title=Lobdell Builds Up Gay Teen With \"Titans\" Bunker - CBR|website=Cbr.com|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref> His run on Teen Titans ended with Volume 4 Issue 30, the series was relaunched soon afterwards.\n\nIn 2011, Lobdell announced a creator-owned book called ''Awesome'' that he was working on in conjunction with Ilias Kyriazis.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bleedingcool.com/2011/07/19/scott-lobdells-awesome-at-san-diego-comic-con/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-07-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722090904/http://www.bleedingcool.com/2011/07/19/scott-lobdells-awesome-at-san-diego-comic-con |archive-date=2011-07-22 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Lobdell began writing a new ''[[The Flash (comic book)| Flash]]'' book focusing on [[Wally West]] following the limited series ''[[Heroes in Crisis]]'', titled ''Flash Forward'', which began publication in November.\n\n===Awards===\nHis work has won him recognition in the comic books industry, such as a nomination for the ''[[Comics Buyer's Guide]]'' Award for \"Favorite Writer\" in 1997.<ref>[http://users.rcn.com/aardy/comics/awards/ Comic Book Awards Almanac] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051210040849/http://users.rcn.com/aardy/comics/awards/ |date=December 10, 2005 }}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn 2011, his portrayal of [[Starfire (Teen Titans)|Starfire/Koriand'r]] in the first issue of ''Red Hood And The Outlaws'', which \"[[Reboot (fiction)|rebooted]]\" its characters, was criticized by some observers. Mathew Peterson of ''MajorSpoilers.com'' described its version of the character as a \"'perfect-10 love doll imaginary girlfriend'\", and stated that a \"juvenile treatment of sexual matters here renders one of the main characters into nothing more than a punch line, and in a book with only three characters, that\u2019s unforgivable.\"<ref name=\"MS1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.majorspoilers.com/new-52-review-red-hood-the-outlaws-1|title=\"New 52\" Review|last=Peterson|first=Matthew|website=MajorSpoilers.com|accessdate=24 October 2011}}</ref> Andrew Hunsaker of ''Craveonline.com'' said that Lobdell's take \"has reduced Princess Koriand'r of Tamaran into essentially a highly advanced [[RealDoll|Real Doll]]. Complete with installing a lack of memory of anything related to humanity,\"<ref name=\"CrO\">{{cite web|url=http://www.craveonline.com/comics/reviews/174866-new-52-review-red-hood-and-the-outlaws-1|title=New 52 Review: Red Hood and the Outlaws #1|last=Hunsacker|first=Andrew|website=Craveonline.com|accessdate=24 October 2011}}</ref> and that it \"seems as if Lobdell has taken great pains to strip all the emotional motivation behind Kori's gregarious outlook and reduce her to nothing more than a sex vessel. It is pretty insulting not only to women, but to male intelligence to boot.\"<ref name=\"CrO\" /> Laura Hudson, editor-in-chief of [[ComicsAlliance]], wrote that \"There's a difference between writing a female character as sexually liberated, and writing her as wish-fulfillment sex object, but Starfire sure is making a case for the latter in [a] charmless scene\"<ref name=\"CA2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comicsalliance.com/2011/09/21/dc-firestar-sex/|title=Parting Shot: DC's New Starfire, WTF|last=Hudson|first=Laura|website=ComicsAlliance.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015130607/http://www.comicsalliance.com/2011/09/21/dc-firestar-sex|archivedate=15 October 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=24 October 2011|df=}}</ref> wherein Starfire defends her offer to have sex with one of the characters by saying that \"love has nothing to do with it\".<ref name=\"RHO1\">{{cite comic|writer=Lobdell, Scott|penciller=Rocafort, Kenneth|inker=Blond|colorist=Blond|letterer=Mangual, Carlos|editor=Bobbie Chase, Katie Kubert|story=I Fought the Law and Kicked Its Butt!|title=Red Hood and the Outlaws|volume=1|issue=1|date=November, 2011|publisher=DC Comics|location=New York}}</ref> Hudson also cited this characterization of Starfire in a later article, remarking that portrayals of women as sexual objects \"don't support sexually liberated women; they undermine them\".<ref name=\"CA1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comicsalliance.com/2011/09/22/starfire-catwoman-sex-superheroine/|title=The Big Sexy Problem with Superheroines and Their 'Liberated Sexuality'|last=Hudson|first=Laura|website=ComicsAlliance.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025001254/http://www.comicsalliance.com/2011/09/22/starfire-catwoman-sex-superheroine|archivedate=25 October 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=24 October 2011|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Lobdell explained that among the reasons he no longer had a social media presence was the unintended spillover from his personal to professional life, and a run-in he'd had with writer [[Ron Marz]] on [[Twitter]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsarama.com/8155-ron-marz-scott-lobdell-on-racism-politics-social-media.html|title=RON MARZ, SCOTT LOBDELL On Racism, Politics & Social Media|website=Newsarama|language=en|access-date=2019-01-30}}</ref> Lobdell had accused Marz of having a \"brain tumor\" in response to comments in which Marz characterized as \"racist\" complaints by some fans that [[Afro-Latin Americans|Afro-Latino]] character [[Miles Morales]] would replace [[Peter Parker]] in ''[[Ultimate Spider-Man]]'', and that African-American actor [[Laurence Fishburne]] had been cast as [[Perry White]] in the film ''[[Man of Steel (film)|Man of Steel]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsarama.com/8155-ron-marz-scott-lobdell-on-racism-politics-social-media.html|title=RON MARZ, SCOTT LOBDELL On Racism, Politics & Social Media|website=Newsarama|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TdxBNEnSjtw|title=Scott Lobdell - How My Twitter Conversation With Ron Marz Changed My Social Media|publisher=[[YouTube]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617223815/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TdxBNEnSjtw|archive-date=17 June 2014|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Scott Lobdell admitted to sexually harassing comic book artist/writer [[MariNaomi]] on stage during a [[Prism Comics]] panel at Long Beach Comic Con. MariNaomi had submitted an article to XoJane<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xojane.com/it-happened-to-me/marinaomi-harassed-comics-panel|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108082218/http://www.xojane.com/it-happened-to-me/marinaomi-harassed-comics-panel|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 January 2014|title=IT HAPPENED TO ME: I Was Sexually Harassed Onstage At a Comic Convention Panel - xoJane|date=8 January 2014|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref> describing how she'd felt harassed by an unnamed fellow panelist, who had questioned her sexuality on stage, made offensive comments about her appearance and Asian features, and made sexually inappropriate jokes about her during the panel. Lobdell later identified himself as the panelist in question, and issued an apology to MariNaomi through [[Heidi MacDonald]] of ComicsBeat.com.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comicsbeat.com/scott-lobdell-i-apologize-to-marinaomi/|title=Scott Lobdell: I apologize to MariNaomi|first=Heidi|last=MacDonald|date=19 December 2013|website=Comicsbeat.com|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Lobdell said that he was enrolled in a gender sensitivity workshop after [[Rich Johnston]] of [[Bleeding Cool|''Bleeding Cool'']] identified him as the subject of an pseudonymous 2016 blog post describing a well-connected comic writer who had stalked and harassed a married female comic creator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://whatchareading.com/wont-end-until-we-stopharassment/|title=Because this behavior won't end until we stand together and make it. #StopHarassment|date=2016-11-17|website=What'cha Reading?|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2019/06/26/sexual-harassment-comics-industry-again/|title=Sexual Harassment and the Comics Industry - Again|website=www.bleedingcool.com|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref> The target of the harassment reported that the subject of her article had sneaked up behind her while she was at a booth and had taken an inappropriate photo of her. She wrote that she was \"worr[ied] that her career prospects [were] jeopardized\" when he had offered her work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2019/06/26/sexual-harassment-comics-industry-again/|title=Sexual Harassment and the Comics Industry \u2013 Again|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bleedingcool.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Comics===\n* ''[[Angel: After the Fall|Angel: Only Human]]''\n* ''[[The Adventures of Cyclops and Phoenix]]'' (4-issue [[Limited series (comics)|mini-series]])\n* ''[[Alpha Flight]]'' vol. 3 #1\u201312\n* ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer comics|Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'' (with [[Fabian Nicieza]]) #47\u201359\n* ''[[Daredevil (Marvel Comics series)|Daredevil]]'' #376\u2013379\n* ''[[The Darkness (comics)|The Darkness]]'' #23\u201338\n* ''[[Excalibur (comics)|Excalibur]]'' #31, #35\u201341, #53, #58\u201360, #68\u201371, #75\u201382\n* ''[[Fantastic Four]]'' #1\u20133, 4\u20135  (with [[Chris Claremont]], 1998)\n* ''[[Flash (Wally West)| Flash Forward]]'' #1-6\n* ''[[Galaxy Quest (comics)|Galaxy Quest]]'' #1\u20135\n* ''[[Gen\u00b9\u00b3]]'' #45\u201354\n* ''[[Generation X (comics)|Generation X]]'' #1\u201328\n* ''[[Ghostbusters (franchise)#Comics/Manga|Ghostbusters: Displaced Aggression]]'' #1\u20134\n* ''[[Iron Man]]'' #1\u20137 (1996)\n* ''Manifest Eternity'' #1\u20136 (Wildstorm, 2006)\n* ''[[Red Hood and the Outlaws]]'' (vol. 1) #1\u201338, (vol. 2) #1-(ongoing) (retitled ''Red Hood: Outlaw'')\n* ''[[Red Hood/Arsenal]]'' (ongoing)\n* ''[[Uncanny X-Men]]'' #286\u2013349, 350 (with [[Steven Seagle]]), #390\u2013393\n* ''[[Wildcats (comics)|Wildcats]]'' #1\u20139 (1997)\n* ''[[X-Factor (comics)|X-Factor]]'' #90\u201395, #106\n* ''[[X-Men]]'' (vol. 2) #6\u201311, #46\u201369, #110\u2013113\n===Television and film===\n* ''[[Godzilla: The Series]]'' S2 ep.3 (1999)\n* ''[[Man of the House (2005 film)|Man of the House]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Mosaic (film)|Mosaic]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Happy Death Day]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Critters Attack!]]'' (2019)\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{gcdb|type=credit|search=Scott+Lobdell|title=Scott Lobdell}}\n*{{comicbookdb|type=creator|id=1806|title=Scott Lobdell}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1245146}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[Excalibur (comics)|Excalibur]]'' writer| before=[[Chris Claremont]]|\nafter=[[Alan Davis]]| years=1991}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[Uncanny X-Men]]'' writer| before=[[John Byrne (comics)|John Byrne]]| after=[[Steven T. Seagle|Steve Seagle]]| years=1992\u20131997}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[Excalibur (comics)|Excalibur]]'' writer| before=[[Alan Davis]]|\nafter=[[Richard Ashford]]| years=1993}}\n{{succession box | title=[[X-Factor (comics)|''X-Factor'' (vol. 1)]] writer| before=[[Peter David]]|\nafter=[[J. M. DeMatteis|J.M. DeMatteis]]| years=1993}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[Generation X (comics)|Generation X]]'' writer| before=None| after=[[James Dale Robinson|James Robinson]]| years=1994\u20131997}}\n{{succession box | title=''[[Iron Man]]'' writer| before=[[Terry Kavanagh]] | after=[[Jeph Loeb]] | years=1996\u20131997<br/>(with [[Jim Lee]])}}\n{{succession box | title=[[X-Men: Legacy|''X-Men'' (vol. 2)]] writer| before=[[Fabian Nicieza